<br>
On the one hand, in the absence of information, assuming that comparable things are of equal value is a first approximation, however, the chart as it stands is incredibly biased, and therefore almost meaningless.  Since everything has equal weight, the results are predetermined simply by your choice of categories.  It reveals little except about the mind of the author.<br>
<br>
It is also inconsistant.  One the one hand, as a crude approximation, everything has the same weight.  On the other hand, the categories attempt to be exhaustive.  If you had chosen a smaller number of more important categories, the results would have been more suggestive.  Counting the number of ticks on a laundry list says more about the list than the relative merits of classes.<br>
<br>
Suppose instead you had chosen 10 categories:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Nuke, Buff, Heal, Tank, Smash, Escape, Travel, Speed, Crowds,</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Abuse</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->,<br>
<br>
and established definitions and criteria for getting a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for each category.  As both the measure and the categories are crude, it would have made a better crude approximation, and might have revealed more.<br>
<br>
As for assigning weights, well in point of fact people are pretty consistant at rating on a scale of 1-5.  This is the basis of an enormous amount of social science.  So if you took these ten categories and weighted each class for them on a 1-5 scale, then results might be more suggestive.  One could use standard deviation to determine how consistant the results were.<br>
<br>
It is a nice idea, but as it stands, it reveals only the bias of the chosen categories.<br>
